			<header>
				<div class="topintro">
					<section class="hero">
						<div class-"texture-overlay"></div>
					<p>Since 2010, CHMI has promoted health market innovations –programs, policies, and practices – that have the potential to improve quality health care for low income populations around the world. Our vision is for health systems around the world to better harness innovation to deliver quality, affordable, and accessible care, especially for the poorest and most vulnerable.</p>
				</div>
			</header>

			<section class="intro">
				<h1 class="TOCtab box">Introduction</h1>
				<p class="opentext">In the past five years, a broad swath of organizations has turned their focus to the exciting innovations in privately delivered healthcare for developing countries. With great potential for success and impact, these innovative programs have become uniquely celebrated in the atmosphere of TED talks, think tanks, and innovation competitions. In 2010, however, the social entrepreneurship bubble had not yet been inflated, and awareness of innovative programs working to improve health in developing countries was low. Without a central repository of information, the organizations seeking to support developing enterprises were unable to identify the innovations that existed and were achieving results. </p>
				<a class="articleDrop" href="#">Read the Introduction</a>
			</section>

			<section class="forward">
				<h1 class="TOCtab box">Forward</h1>
				<h2 class="subtitle">The Five C’s of Vibrant Innovation Ecosystems</h2>
				<a class="articleDrop" href="#">Read the Forward</a>
			</section>

			<section class="database">
				<h1 class="TOCtab box">Programs Database</h1>
				<h2 class="subtitle">A Global Platform for Innovations in Health</h2>
				<p class="article alwaysShow">CHMI provides free access to the world’s most comprehensive database of innovative health programs in developing countries, catalyzing new partnerships and opportunities to take organizations to scale. CHMI profiles programs that work in low- and middle- income countries and serve low-income communities, spanning a broad spectrum of service delivery, financing, regulatory, and process/product-oriented innovations. Each program is captured through a standardized profile documenting information about the program’s operational design, including health focus, targeted populations, funding sources, and where available, results to date.</p>
				<p class="article alwaysShow">This database is designed to increase collective understanding about the scale, scope, and results of innovative health approaches. The information is underpinned by a framework categorizing each innovation’s main ‘approach’ and standardizes the way information is collected and reported – including performance results where available. The database launched in July 2010 with an initial set of 600 profiled programs, and has evolved significantly since launch.</p>
			</section>
			<section class="pipeline">
				<h1 class="TOCtab box">A Pipeline to Opportunities</h1>
				<h3 class="subheader">CHMI’s database reduces information and due diligence costs for challenge funds, competitions, and global institutions seeking to highlight promising innovations.</h3>

			</section>
			<section class="evidence">
				<h1 class="TOCtab box">Increasing the Evidence Base</h1>
				<h2 class="subtitle"> Informing the evolution of health markets with 'what works' in innovation</h2>
				<h3 class="subheader">CHMI analyzes the many facets of data collected on health innovations to produce influential knowledge products informing adoption of best practices and policies.</h3>
				<p class="opentext">Global development stakeholders are constantly in search of promising and scalable solutions to fundamental quality and access challenges related to basic services for the poor. There is great demand from all stakeholders, from funders to program implementers, for a greater degree of evidence and lessons on which types of program models achieve results.</p>
				<div class="subRes">
					<h3 class="subsection">Highlighting What Works</h3>
					<p class="results showtext">CHMI conducts monthly analyses on the 1,400 programs in the database to better understand trends in niche market approaches including social franchising, innovations in Nigeria, and technology in Maternal Newborn and Child Health</p>
